\i0 "Hometown Glory" is the first single from Adele's debut album 19, released on 22 October 2007 in the United Kingdom. In 2008, the song was re-released as her fourth single. Adele wrote the song in 10 minutes after her mother tried to persuade her to leave her home town of West Norwood in London for university.\
\
The song \'93Hometown Glory\'94 is about Adele missing her hometown of London. However, the song can relate to anyone\'92s home. In the first verse, the singer is narrating a moment of reminiscing. \'93I\'92ve been walking in the same way as I did/Missing out the cracks in the pavement/And turning my heel and strutting my feet\'94 It sounds like she is just trying to remember how calm everything back was. The lines \'93Is there anything I can do for you dear?/Is there anyone I could call?\'94 is referring to familiar voice in Adele's life, perhaps her mother or father. The next line refers to Adele's sense of unfamiliarity with where she is going \'93No and thank you, please Madam/I ain\'92t lost, just wandering\'94. The second half of the song discusses political conflict in London and is a call for solidarity among the people. "I like it in the city when two worlds collide/You get the people and the government/Everybody taking different sides". Adele places herself firmly on the side of ordinary people. The line is perhaps also a reference to the "authority" of her mother forcing her to go to school outside of London. Adele sees herself as heroically challenging this authority.
